{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505660"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2467"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2467"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.09,0.55,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80528"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43859"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to his general practitioner for review after a recent admission to hospital with an episode of acute pancreatitis. This was the first time he had experienced this problem and has made some significant lifestyle changes since then, including reducing his alcohol intake and quitting smoking. He remains asymptomatic since his discharge. His most recent laboratory investigations since his discharge are all within normal range, apart from his HbA1c, which is 9%. He was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes five years ago and has been managing with lifestyle changes and metformin extended release 1g twice daily since then.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe takes perindopril for high blood pressure and atorvastatin for high cholesterol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has a blood pressure of 130/93 mmHg, pulse 77/min and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and abdominal examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat the HbA1c again in three months","Start a long acting insulin at night","Start empagliflozin","Start sitagliptin","Start semaglutide injections"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in managing this patient\u0027s type 2 diabetes is to start an SGLT2 inhibitor, such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eempagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E. This choice is supported by the need to lower his HbA1c, which is currently at 9%, and the additional cardiovascular and renal protective benefits of SGLT2 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating the HbA1c in three months\u003C/strong\u003E without changing the treatment plan is not appropriate given the high HbA1c level. Current guidelines recommend intensifying treatment to achieve glycaemic targets rather than delaying intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting a long-acting insulin\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered, but it is generally reserved for later stages of treatment due to the risks of hypoglycaemia and the burden of injections. Oral medications are preferred when possible, especially in patients who may be reluctant to start insulin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESitagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E is a DPP-4 inhibitor, and \u003Cstrong\u003Esemaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E is a GLP-1 agonist. Both are contraindicated in patients with a history of pancreatitis due to the potential risk of contributing to pancreatitis. Therefore, these options are not suitable for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, empagliflozin is the most appropriate choice due to its efficacy in lowering HbA1c, its additional benefits in cardiovascular and renal protection, and its suitability given the patient\u0027s recent history of pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["DPP-4 inhibitors and GLP-1 agonists are contraindicated if the patient has a history of pancreatitis.","SGLT-2 inhibitors provide cardiovascular and renal protection in patients with type 2 diabetes.","Aggressive management of type 2 diabetes aims to achieve target HbA1c levels promptly."],"references":["Australian Diabetes Society (ADS) Contributors, 2020. Australian Type 2 Diabetes Management Algorithm (Internet). Access at: http://t2d.diabetessociety.com.au/documents/4S3vDJz3.pdf.","Weinberg Sibony R, Segev O, Dor S, Raz I. Drug Therapies for Diabetes. Int J Mol Sci. 2023 Dec 5;24(24):17147. doi: 10.3390/ijms242417147. PMID: 38138975; PMCID: PMC10742594. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38138975/","Sizar O, Podder V, Talati R. Empagliflozin. 2023 May 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30422520. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30422520/","Forycka J, Hajdys J, Krzemi\u0144ska J, Wilczopolski P, Wronka M, M\u0142ynarska E, Rysz J, Franczyk B. New Insights into the Use of Empagliflozin-A Comprehensive Review. Biomedicines. 2022 Dec 19;10(12):3294. doi: 10.3390/biomedicines10123294. PMID: 36552050; PMCID: PMC9775057. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9775057/","National Diabetes Service Scheme. Australian Type 2 Diabetes glycaemic Management Algorithm. 2024 [cited 2024 Apr 10]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-rac..."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80528"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2467"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80528"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-10T18:30:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-10T18:31:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2467"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97997"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"d